\section{Introduction}
Mathematical models are often used in epidemiology to understand how infectious diseases spread through a population.  One of the most widely used models is the SIR model, which separates a population into susceptible, infectious, and recovered groups.  

In this project, we investigated how well the SIR model can describe the spread of COVID-19 in New York State.  We chose New York because it experienced a well-documented and significant early outbreak of COVID-19, and the availability of detailed, publicly accessible statewide data makes it well-suited for quantitative analysis.  Using this data, we numerically solved the SIR system using a standard ODE solver and estimated the model parameters using least squares.  We then compared the model’s output to observed COVID-19 case data to assess the model’s accuracy and limitations.

\subsection*{SIR Model}
The SIR model is a mathematical model used in epidemiology to describe and predict the spread of infectious diseases.  To start, it divides the population into three groups: $S(t)$ (susceptible), $I(t)$ (infectious), and $R(t)$ (recovered).  The total population is assumed constant:
\[
N = S(t) + I(t) + R(t).
\]

The model describes how individuals move between these groups using a system of differential equations:
\[
\frac{dS}{dt} = -\beta \frac{S(t) I(t)}{N},
\]
\[
\frac{dI}{dt} = \beta \frac{S(t) I(t)}{N} - \gamma I(t),
\]
\[
\frac{dR}{dt} = \gamma I(t).
\]
\noindent where $\beta$ represents the transmission rate, describing how frequently susceptible and infectious individuals interact to produce new infections, and $\gamma$ represents the recovery rate, describing the rate at which infectious individuals recover and move into the recovered group.

The susceptible population decreases as susceptible individuals come into contact with infectious individuals and become infected.  The infectious population increases through new infections and decreases as individuals recover.  The recovered population increases as infectious individuals move out of the infectious group.

We chose to use the SIR model because it provides a simple framework for studying disease spread using only a small number of variables and parameters.  However, this simplicity comes from several underlying assumptions:
\begin{itemize}
    \item \textbf{Closed population:} The total population $N$ remains constant over time, with no births, deaths, or migration.
    
    \item \textbf{Homogeneous mixing:} Individuals interact uniformly, meaning every susceptible individual has an equal chance of coming into contact with an infectious individual.
    
    \item \textbf{Constant parameters:} The transmission rate $\beta$ and recovery rate $\gamma$ are assumed to remain constant over time.
    
    \item \textbf{Permanent immunity:} Individuals who recover from the disease are assumed to gain complete and lasting immunity.
    \end{itemize}


Although COVID-19 is more complicated than the assumptions of a basic SIR model, the model is still useful as a first approximation, especially during the early stage of an outbreak.

\section{Data}

We used COVID-19 case data from the COVID-19 Data Hub \cite{covidhub}.  This dataset aggregates official government-reported COVID-19 data into a unified and standardized format suitable for epidemiological analysis.

The data was organized as a time series of confirmed COVID-19 cases.  For this project, we focused on the Omicron wave in New York State, specifically from December 1, 2021 to February 15, 2022.  This period captures a distinct surge in infections and allows the use of a single-wave SIR model.

A limitation of the dataset is that it does not directly measure the number of currently infectious individuals, as it reports confirmed case counts rather than active infections.  As a result, additional processing is required to construct quantities that are comparable to the compartments of the SIR model.


\section{Methods}

\subsection*{Data Processing}

COVID-19 case data for New York State was organized as a time series using the reported test date.  The dataset was restricted to the Omicron wave, from December 1, 2021 to February 15, 2022.

Daily new cases were extracted and converted to numeric values.  Because the SIR model tracks the number of currently infectious individuals, an estimate of the infectious population was constructed using a 7-day rolling sum of reported daily cases, reflecting an assumed infectious period of approximately one week.  Observations with insufficient data for this calculation were removed.  Additionally, population values were scaled to millions.

\subsection*{Numerical Solution}

The system of differential equations was solved numerically using the \texttt{ode} function from the \texttt{deSolve} package in R.  This function applies standard numerical ODE solvers to approximate the solution over time.

Initial conditions were defined using the first observed value of the estimated infectious population:
\[
I_0 = \text{initial estimated infectious population}, \quad
S_0 = N - I_0, \quad
R_0 = 0.
\]

\subsection*{Parameter Estimation}

The parameters $\beta$ and $\gamma$ were estimated by minimizing the difference between the model-predicted infectious population and the observed infectious data.

For each pair $(\beta, \gamma)$, the SIR system was solved numerically to generate $I_{\text{model}}(t)$.  This was compared to the observed infectious population $I_{\text{data}}(t)$ using the mean squared error:
\[
\text{MSE} = \frac{1}{n} \sum_{t=1}^{n} \left( I_{\text{model}}(t) - I_{\text{data}}(t) \right)^2.
\]

A bounded optimization algorithm (L-BFGS-B) was used to ensure that parameter values remained positive.


\subsection*{Model Evaluation}

Using the optimized parameters, the SIR system was solved to obtain trajectories for $S(t)$, $I(t)$, and $R(t)$.  These were compared to the estimated observed infectious population to evaluate how well the model captured the dynamics of the outbreak.



